Our families are extension of our Ambassadors families and our community. Our voice is to speak for our family as well as for our community: to inform when tragedy happens that is felt from our community and abroad. We are a family of relocation or families coming from other states that build a foundation for the next generation. On Saturday, we lost Fannie L. Hickman, mother of our ambassador Eli Hickman. She was a craftswoman. People collected her beadwork and wore with pride. Her work has been seen at our events, social events and powwows from Texas to Oklahoma to Mississippi. She raised a family that are still making an impact in the American Indian community and with her grandchildren coming up to show our next generational responsibility. Fannie L. Hickman is making her trip back home to Mississippi to be laid to rest. Our American Indian community sends our prayers and healing thoughts to her family for peace and love. AT&T has increased the play time to 5 minutes on each showing and they are adding a 4th viewing at approximately 9:24pm beginning Friday November 20th.* Celebrating Native American Heritage Month (art/work by @Brian Larney of yahvlane). Through the many aspects of work and relationships forged through American Indian Heritage Day in Texas as an organization so many things have happened in our existence. One relationship built has been that with ICAE of AT&T. ICAE being the Intertribal Council of AT&T Employees. Through the past several years each organization has taught, learned, and supported many different efforts by each other. This is not only an accomplishment by an artist but a member of our native community and in turn a win to be celebrated and uplifted by us all. It is not only a win by a corporation to show diversity but a win on the side of solidarity that should be embraced and acknowledged as just the beginning of them uplifting community discourse. This is more than just a message. This is more than just Native American Heritage month, it is a door being opened for our youth, for our future, to know we can proudly say who we are and WE ARE HERE. in the Los Angeles","profileImage":"https://scontent-sea1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.6435-9/cp0/c47.0.50.50a/p50x50/133701361_10158684659253213_2488061764996088255_n.jpg?_nc_cat=109&ccb=1-5&_nc_sid=ac9ee4&_nc_ohc=VeQo4K-ra2EAX_KPHPV&_nc_ht=scontent-sea1-1.xx&oh=00_AT_HfltSeM6WX27crrH0TedMzanmT_RhKZvOmhwVWg5yjg&oe=61FF219F","subscriberCount":20544,"url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/1414787968736726","platform":"Facebook","platformId":"1414787968736726","accountType":"facebook_group","pageCategory":"none","verified":false},"languageCode":"en","legacyId":0,"id":"9984344|2786950544853788"},{"platformId":"1869720093284086_2771885943067492","platform":"Facebook","date":"2020-11-19 07:42:13","updated":"2021-11-06 20:49:28","type":"photo","description":"It has been a humbling experience this past week where we heard from all of you. Some of you knew us well, some of you didn’t, at all. To all our shining knights, we dedicate this post to you, who had enough faith in complete strangers on the internet and opened your hearts and supported our cause.\n\nWe would like you to know us a bit better and understand our motivations. No one in their right minds tries to raise 16 crores over the internet. But we are, and here’s why...\n\nWe are Priyanka and Mihir Kamat, a young couple who recently welcomed our beautiful daughter Teera into the world. We were married for 4 years, and this August we became a family of three. Both of us have been born and brought up in Mumbai, in families that taught us traditional, humble Maharashtrian values. \n\nTeera was born a happy, cheerful baby. The gleam in her eyes told us she was going to grow up a smart, mischievous yet loving girl. As weeks went by we noticed her having heavy breathing patterns and she would take a lot of time feeding, sometimes even hours. We simply dismissed it as normal; she was just a bit delicate and still had a lot of growing to do.\n\nBut all was not well. Teera needed to see a doctor for multiple issues, severe dehydration, heavy breathing, choking on feeds. COVID didn’t help, and we finally found a doctor in our area that noticed her feeding issues. She recommended we start bottle feeding our baby until she regains her health.\n\nDuring the next 15 days, she started feeding properly and also started gaining weight which was a good sign for us. But on the day of her vaccination, her doctor noticed her choking on the first drops of vaccine and though she looked healthy, she had no resistance in her hands and her right leg did not move an inch. If it wasn't for Teera's doctor, we would have never thought of investigating these symptoms further.\n\nWe went to a pediatric neurologist who mentioned that she might have hypotonia, slow reflexes, paradoxical respiration, and a weak cry. She needed to be evaluated to confirm any muscle or nerve issues. Next day itself we got her EMG test done. We did not understand the test much but saw that our baby was poked with 8 needles in different parts of her limbs and she screamed! We held her hands quietly, with a heavy heart, hoping she never has to go through something like this again.\n\nThe test results were full of medical language, and then the doctor called us in to discuss, another ominous sign. A genetic test, he said, there was a good chance she has SMA. We watched them take vials of blood from her little body, and prayed hard that it wasn’t the scary disease the doctor told us about. The tests will definitely come back negative, we told ourselves. We were convincing each other that our baby is just a late bloomer and the tests are all wrong.\n\nPOSITIVE…\n\nWe were completely devastated. Our 2 month baby had SMA (Spinal Muscular Atrophy) Type1, the most severe form of a rare genetic disease. A disease that attacks the central nervous system, killing nerves and causing muscle weakness until the entire body gives up. The doctors told us about her life limiting condition and that she would not make it past her 2nd birthday if left untreated. There were only 3, very expensive, treatment options available, none of which are available in India, and all of them will need to be imported. And only one of these options shows any real promise.\n\nZOLGENSMA, a one-time gene therapy, is priced commercially at USD $2.1 million. A drug that could potentially cure our daughter would cost us close to 16 crores INR, a mind boggling sum of money and completely out of capacity for middle class families like ours. Unbelievable, that one injection costs that much money.\n\nThe only silver lining in all this is that even though we live in a country where genetic testing is not common, we have diagnosed her condition early which gives us a fighting chance.\n\nPlease share and support Teera and help us spread awareness about the disease. Here is a link to our fundraiser - https://www.impactguru.com/fundraiser/donate-to-teera\n\nP.S. In today’s world where wearing a mask is a necessity, Teera hates people with masks. She has had her blood drawn 4 times, always from masked people. Yesterday she looked in my eyes and screamed, I was wearing a mask.","message":"With Mihir.and Indian mascots?” The Native elder responded, “Here’s what you’ve got to understand. When you look at black people, you see ghosts of all the slavery and the rapes and the hangings and the chains. When you look at Jews, you see ghosts of all those bodies piled up in death camps. And those ghosts keep you trying to do the right thing. “But when you look at us you don’t see the ghosts of the little babies with their heads smashed in by rifle butts at the Big Hole, or the old folks dying by the side of the trail on the way to Oklahoma while their families cried and tried to make them comfortable, or the dead mothers at Wounded Knee or the little kids at Sand Creek who were shot for target practice. You don’t see any ghosts at all. “Instead you see casinos and drunks and junk cars and shacks. “Well, we see those ghosts. And they make our hearts sad and they hurt our little children. And when we try to say something, you tell us, ‘Get over it. This is America. Look at the American dream.’ But as long as you’re calling us Redskins and doing tomahawk chops, we can’t look at the American dream, because those things remind us that we are not real human beings to you. And when people aren’t humans, you can turn them into slaves or kill six million of them or shoot them down with Hotchkiss guns and throw them into mass graves at Wounded Knee. “No, we’re not looking at the American dream. And why should we? We still haven’t woken up from the American nightmare. ~from \"Neither Wolf Nor Dog\", a book by Kent Nerburn.\nThanks Lita 06:07:28","updated":"2022-01-06 20:39:22","type":"photo","description":"HONOR. Warrior Women of the Rock.\nWomen, Hearts of resilience, resistance, resurgence. Here, were photographed several of the powerful, dedicated women that kept the day-to-day operations on the Rock going during the, \"Indian Occupation\" from 1969-1970. From left to right, Sue Tiger, Shirley (Garcia) Guevera, Sandra Aguilar, Eldy Bratt, Justine Moppin, Rosalie McKay and Lola Cecelia Pepion, Blackfeet From Montana. They all made sure people were fed, the living arrangements were made bearable as possible, and helped maintain as much normalcy for the families, children and fellow occupiers. There were many others too. This picture was taken years later during one of the re-unions, the 20th or 30th anniversary of the Occupation, possibly 1980 or 1990. The Occupation of Alcatraz was an occupation of Alcatraz Island by 89 indigenous individuals of allied native nations who called themselves, Indians of All Tribes (IOAT).According to the IOAT, the Treaty of Fort Laramie (1868) between the U.S. and the Lakota, all retired, abandoned or out-of-use federal land was returned to the Native people from whom it was taken. Since Alcatraz penitentiary had been closed on March 21, 1963, and the island had been declared surplus federal property in 1964, a number of activists felt the island qualified for a reclamation. The Alcatraz Occupation lasted for nineteen months, from November 20, 1969, to June 11, 1971, and was forcibly ended by the U.S. government. The Occupation of Alcatraz had a direct effect on, 'federal Indian policy' and, with its visible results and hard won victories, established a precedent for later Indigenous TIA","postUrl":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/1869720093284086/permalink/2775836252672461","subscriberCount":34569,"score":1.95,"statistics":{"actual":{"likeCount":5,"shareCount":0,"commentCount":34,"loveCount":0,"wowCount":0,"hahaCount":0,"sadCount":0,"angryCount":0,"thankfulCount":0,"careCount":0},"expected":{"likeCount":2,"shareCount":1,"commentCount":8,"loveCount":2,"wowCount":2,"hahaCount":3,"sadCount":2,"angryCount":0,"thankfulCount":0,"careCount":2}},"account":{"id":3257521,"name":"Indians in Seattle Bellevue Redmond Bothell Sammamish Kent Kirkland Renton","profileImage":"https://scontent-sea1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.18169-9/cp0/c43.0.50.50a/p50x50/18118860_10211918624016347_4919138714841444567_n.jpg?_nc_cat=106&ccb=1-5&_nc_sid=ac9ee4&_nc_ohc=5uUtmGdl32AAX_VMxSs&_nc_ht=scontent-sea1-1.xx&oh=00_AT-e8vUYsedZoI1-Ezq6nUUgQptcovkzkyI7fVfnURr0hQ&oe=61FDEF44","subscriberCount":43948,"url":"https://www.facebook.com/1869720093284086","platform":"Facebook","platformId":"1869720093284086","accountType":"facebook_group","pageCategory":"none","verified":false},"languageCode":"en","legacyId":0,"id":"3257521|2775836252672461"},{"platformId":"503055433070371_4767354869973718","platform":"Facebook","date":"2020-11-29 04:16:58","updated":"2022-01-06 20:39:22","type":"photo","description":"The Haudenosaunee (Iroquois) Thanksgiving Address\n\n“Ohenton Kariwahtekwen”\n\nThe Iroquois Thanksgiving Address is a prayer of gratitude dating back more than 1,000 years. It is still spoken at many Iroquois ceremonial, social and governmental gatherings, and is often recited by traditional Haudenosaunee at the start and end of each day.\n\nOhenton Karihwatehkwen means “The Words That Come Before All Else.”\n\nThe People\nToday we have gathered and we see that the cycles of life continue. We have been given the duty to live in balance and harmony with each other and all living things. So now, we bring our minds together as one as we give greetings and thanks to each other as people. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Earth Mother\nWe are all thankful to our Mother, the Earth, for she gives us all that we need for life. She supports our feet as we walk about upon her. It gives us joy that she continues to care for us as she has from the beginning of time. To our mother, we send greetings and thanks. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Waters\nWe give thanks to all the waters of the world for quenching our thirst and providing us with strength. Water is life. We know its power in many forms-waterfalls and rain, mists and streams, rivers and oceans. With one mind, we send greetings and thanks to the spirit of Water. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Fish\nWe turn our minds to the all the Fish life in the water. They were instructed to cleanse and purify the water. They also give themselves to us as food. We are grateful that we can still find pure water. So, we turn now to the Fish and send our greetings and thanks. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Plants\nNow we turn toward the vast fields of Plant life. As far as the eye can see, the Plants grow, working many wonders. They sustain many life forms. With our minds gathered together, we give thanks and look forward to seeing Plant life for many generations to come. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Food Plants\nWith one mind, we turn to honor and thank all the Food Plants we harvest from the garden. Since the beginning of time, the grains, vegetables, beans and berries have helped the people survive. Many other living things draw strength from them too. We gather all the Plant Foods together as one and send them a greeting of thanks. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Medicine Herbs\nNow we turn to all the Medicine herbs of the world. From the beginning they were instructed to take away sickness. They are always waiting and ready to heal us. We are happy there are still among us those special few who remember how to use these plants for healing. With one mind, we send greetings and thanks to the Medicines and to the keepers of the Medicines. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Animals\nWe gather our minds together to send greetings and thanks to all the Animal life in the world. They have many things to teach us as people. We are honored by them when they give up their lives so we may use their bodies as food for our people. We see them near our homes and in the deep forests. We are glad they are still here and we hope that it will always be so.  Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Trees\nWe now turn our thoughts to the Trees. The Earth has many families of Trees who have their own instructions and uses. Some provide us with shelter and shade, others with fruit, beauty and other useful things. Many people of the world use a Tree as a symbol of peace and strength. With one mind, we greet and thank the Tree life. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Birds\nWe put our minds together as one and thank all the Birds who move and fly about over our heads. The Creator gave them beautiful songs. Each day they remind us to enjoy and appreciate life. The Eagle was chosen to be their leader. To all the Birds-from the smallest to the largest-we send our joyful greetings and thanks. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Four Winds\nWe are all thankful to the powers we know as the Four Winds. We hear their voices in the moving air as they refresh us and purify the air we breathe. They help us to bring the change of seasons. From the four directions they come, bringing us messages and giving us strength. With one mind, we send our greetings and thanks to the Four Winds. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Thunderers\nNow we turn to the west where our grandfathers, the Thunder Beings, live. With lightning and thundering voices, they bring with them the water that renews life. We are thankful that they keep those evil things made by Okwiseres underground. We bring our minds together as one to send greetings and thanks to our Grandfathers, the Thunderers. Now our minds are one.\n\nThe Sun\nWe now send greetings and thanks to our eldest Brother, the Sun. Each day without fail he travels the sky from east to west, bringing the light of a new day. He is the source of all the fires of life. With one mind, we send greetings and thanks to our Brother, the Sun. Now our minds are one.\n\nGrandmother Moon\nWe put our minds together to give thanks to our oldest Grandmother, the finalists for the Global Citizen Prize. She is only Indian to be shortlisted for her tireless work towards educating women on menstrual hygiene in Mumbai’s slums and other underprivileged areas. Her nonprofit – Myna Mahila Foundation – provides menstrual health products to and creates livelihood opportunities for economically disadvantaged women. Alongside social entrepreneurship, she is pursuing PhD in Health Policy and Economics at Stanford University in California. If Suhani Jalota happens to win the Global Citizen Prize: Cisco Youth Leadership Award 2020, she will receive a grant worth US$ 250,000 for her nonprofit organization. \n\nSuhani is one of the few individuals who Meghan Markle chose to meet during her first trip to India in 2017. Mesmerized by Suhani’s menstrual taboo-breaking initiatives, Meghan became an advocate of her nonprofit. She invited Suhani to represent her Myna Mahila Foundation in her royal wedding and asked her guests to donate to Suhani’s organization instead of a wedding gift. Suhani Jalota began her philanthropic journey way back in 2015 and motivated women to break stereotypes around menstruation. She received the Glamor Woman of the Year Award in 2016 and Queen’s Young Leader Award in 2017. Her NGO plans to bring 2 million women within the ambit of menstrual hygiene by the end of 2025.","message":"26-year-old Suhani Jalota is among the three finalists for the Global Citizen Prize. She is only Indian to be shortlisted for her tireless work towards educating women on menstrual hygiene in Mumbai’s slums and other underprivileged areas. Her nonprofit – Myna Mahila Foundation – provides menstrual health products to and creates livelihood opportunities for economically disadvantaged women. Alongside social entrepreneurship, she is pursuing PhD in Health Policy and Economics at Stanford University in California. If Suhani Jalota happens to win the Global Citizen Prize: Cisco Youth Leadership Award 2020, she will receive a grant worth US$ 250,000 for her nonprofit organization. Suhani is one of the few individuals who Meghan Markle chose to meet during her first trip to India in 2017. Mesmerized by Suhani’s menstrual taboo-breaking initiatives, Meghan became an advocate of her nonprofit. She invited Suhani to represent her Myna Mahila Foundation in her royal wedding and asked her guests to donate to Suhani’s organization instead of a wedding gift. Suhani Jalota began her philanthropic journey way back in 2015 and motivated women to break stereotypes around menstruation. She received the Glamor Woman of the Year Award in 2016 and Queen’s Young Leader Award in 2017. Earlier Ram Mahavadi played a good knock of 38 of 48 balls with three boundaries. Defending 258 TCA bowlers got Cricketminds for 172 all out in 36 overs . Pick of the bowlers were Soorya selvaKumar 2 for 25 of seven overs , Aishik Ghosh 2 for 31 and centurion Rishi ramesh 3 for 12 in 5 overs including a hatrick. Good come back team ! Well done! concerned me and the response from CNN CEO Jeff Zucker. \n \nDear Mr. Zucker: \n \nOn behalf of the Choctaw Nation of Oklahoma (Choctaw Nation), I am writing to express my profound disappointment with CNN’s lack of respect and dignity provided to Native American voters during the 2020 election.\n \nAs CNN reported exit polls on election night, Native Americans across the Nation were shocked and deeply offended to see the reporting of critical Native American voters being referred to as “something else.” \n \nNative Americans play a critical role in the elections of this great country. Yet for centuries we have had to continually fight for the right to vote. The Indian Citizenship Act of 1924 granted citizenship to all Native Americans. However, it was not until 1957 through the advocacy of our ancestors before state governments that all Native Americans were allowed to vote throughout the country. Today, we continue to fight against voter discrimination. \n \nDespite these challenges, we have continually turned out in unprecedented numbers and have proven that we can influence elections. To ensure our voices are heard, Native Americans have proudly spent countless hours canvassing, phone banking, registering our members to vote, volunteering on campaigns, and lifting our voices up to be heard. We have spent many dollars to increase voter turnout in our communities and are proud of the progress that we have made. From Maine to Florida, across the great plains to the southwestern deserts, into the tundra of Alaska and the islands of Hawaii, we continue to come out to vote. \n \nWe have fought long and hard to maintain our place and existence in this world. Yet, CNN’s complete disregard of the contributions of Native American voters as demonstrated by its offensive reporting only perpetuates the continued marginalization of our communities and creates a snowball effect that rolls downhill into federal, state, and local governments and neighboring communities that Native American people are not here.\n \nThe Choctaw Nation Tribal Council hopes CNN will reconcile its inappropriate and offensive actions by properly recognizing the power and influence of the Native American vote and discontinuing its use of “something else” in future reporting. Yakoke (thank you) for considering the views and concerns of the Choctaw Nation regarding this matter. \n \nYakoke! (Thank you)\n \nGary Batton, Chief\nChoctaw Nation of Oklahoma \n________________________________________\n\nDear Chief Batton,\n \nThank you for your email. One relationship built has been that with ICAE of AT&T. ICAE being the Intertribal Council of AT&T Employees. Through the past several years each organization has taught, learned, and supported many different efforts by each other. This is not only an accomplishment by an artist but a member of our native community and in turn a win to be celebrated and uplifted by us all. It is not only a win by a corporation to show diversity but a win on the side of solidarity that should be embraced and acknowledged as just the beginning of them uplifting community discourse. This is more than just a message. This is more than just Native American Heritage month, it is a door being opened for our youth, for our future, to know we can proudly say who we are and WE ARE HERE.\n\nWe encourage our people, our community, our genuine allies, and all of our friends and family to visit this 7 Story Tall Digital Billboard in AT&T's Discovery District located in Downtown Dallas (off of Commerce St near Neiman Marcus). It has been observed that many passengers buy the tickets to India transiting through Istanbul and other third-country transit points like Doha, Oman, Dubai, etc. Once they reach Istanbul, they are refused the onward boarding pass because of the travel restrictions to India. As a result, they get stuck in the transit area. Within a day or two, their COVID Test validity also expires, which is a prerequisite to boarding in most of the airlines. Since Turkey has lifted all air travel restrictions since June 2020, flights especially those operated by Turkish Airlines, are plying to Turkey. It has been observed that many passengers buy the tickets to India transiting through Istanbul and other third-country transit points like Doha, Oman, Dubai, etc. Once they reach Istanbul, they are refused the onward boarding pass because of the travel restrictions to India. As a result, they get stuck in the transit area. Within a day or two, their COVID Test validity also expires, which is a prerequisite to boarding in most of the airlines.
